:::summary
Mountains are the great elevated landforms of the Earth — dramatic expressions of the planet's geological dynamism — rising from the humble hills of the British Isles to the sublime heights of the Himalayas. They have shaped the course of human history by forming barriers, providing resources, and inspiring awe; and they occupy a central place in the biblical narrative, from Sinai to Zion to the Mount of Olives, as the places where heaven and earth most vividly meet.
:::

